
[1]derogatory

   DEROGATORY, a.

   1. Detracting or tending to lessen by taking something from; that
   lessens the extent, effect or value; with to. Let us entertain no
   opinions derogatory to the honor of God, or his moral government. Let
   us say nothing derogatory to the merit of our neighbor.

   2. A derogatory clause in a testament, is a sentence or secret
   character inserted by the testator, of which he reserves the knowledge
   to himself, with a condition that no will be may make hereafter shall
   be valid, unless this clause is inserted word for word; a precaution to
   guard against later wills extorted by violence or obtained by
   suggestion.
